Q34: We move at a slower pace and appreciate little things.  We have learned compassion and understanding for all others and know never to judge someone else's capabilities as Colton is very smart yet has issues with speech and other odd behaviors to someone else's eye.  He is always happy, he loves being home and enjoying simple silly games with our family.  Our youngest son has developed a compassion for all kids and always tries to help others because thats what we all do for our family. Colton is so quickly witty with us, sometimes it gets him in trouble with others.  He gets fixated on things; how a roomba operates, how a dishwasher breaks, how an oven works, he has to study every intricate detail and piece of machinery and he's really intelligent with these topics and he loves to build replicas of the intricate details of these machines and it's fascinating to see.  He is so extremely creative.
Q35: Patience whether I think I have it or not, Colton does not seem to understand "Hurry Up, were are going to be late.  He gets upset easily so losing my patience is not an option because I have seen it would ruin his whole day.  He is very sweet, soft spoken, kind, and polite.  He doesn't seem to understand embarrassment or understand when we say certain things he can hurt another's feelings and he's very literal.  If you ask him a question, I  typically caution people because he doesn't have a filter and WILL tell the truth, which is an awesome quality, I don't think he has any capability of lying, even if he thought he'd get in trouble or for any reason, he has always told the truth. For example: His grandma who is somewhat sensitive asked if he liked dinner she made, his response, "no, it was really gross but i tried one bite of everything." Or if you tell him an idiom, he typically will not understand it, for example before we taught him some of those concepts, if I was in a hurry, I'd say, "Come on kids, we have to hit the pavement." Colton literally went outside and smacked the concrete driveway.  We get a lot of laughs from him, though at the age of 10 he has remembered what we have told him and now knows what many mean.  Sometimes, I think I need to be more like him, never in a hurry, stops and spots things here and there to observe, and always tells the truth.

To look out for and always be considerate of people with disabilities, especially children.

Q34: She has shown everyone that great things can happen in spite of barriers. Her condition helps to provide a better understanding of others' special needs. She has brought so much love. I have grown stronger while fighting for her to get what she needs and watching her succeed in what she has set out to do.
Q35: To help others through their struggles with special needs. It has taught me that advocacy is such a crucial component in learning to help your child who is different than others. I have learned that there are so many people, regardless of their title (teachers, doctors, etc) who will judge and discriminate an individual with special needs, no matter the age, simply due to a lack of understanding about their condition. We have all learned, including my daughter, that SLOS is not recognized or understood by society or the medical and educational world, nearly as much as it needs to be.

Q34: She makes us better people; we have truly learned how to love unconditionally. We have had to learn patience in a way that we didn't understand before she came along. She has taught us that the only way we can get through life with a child like her is to rely fully on God for His grace in order to deal with all the stress and concern that comes with having a medically complex and fragile child. She has truly made our lives better, and we are so thankful God chose to send her to our family.

Q35: The same as above.  We lost Austin in February 2018 at the age of 22.  Our physician told us he would not make it to his first birthday, then his second.  Austin was a fighter and loved his life.  Every minute of it!  He laughed and taught us how to enjoy our blessings.   Austin led the path of inclusion in our school district and was the first student from the MD classroom in a wheelchair to graduate high school and walk across the State Theatre (part of Playhouse Square in Cleveland) with his class.   People have told us throughout his life how much they had learned by knowing and loving Austin.  I miss him every day.
